│ IR contains a loop with a recurrence relation defined by a PHI node and an `add`           │
│ instruction. The recurrence is `%conv678.i.i_next = add i8 0, %conv678.i.i`. This is not a │
│ reduction; it simply propagates the initial value of the PHI node through the loop         │
│ iterations. However, the Loop Vectorizer misidentifies this as an addition                 │
│ reduction.\n\n### Analyzing `opt`'s Log ###\n\nThe Alive2 verification fails, showing that │
│ the original code returns `1` while the vectorized code returns `2`. This discrepancy      │
│ arises because the vectorizer generates code to perform a vector reduction `add <i8 1, i8  │
│ 1>`, which results in `2`. The correct behavior would be to recognize that the value `1`   │
│ is loop-invariant after the first iteration.\n\nThe suspicious PHI node in the vectorized  │
│ code, `%vec.phi = phi <2 x i8> [ <i8 1, i8 0>, %vector.ph ], [ splat (i8 1), %vector.body  │
│ ]`, confirms that the vectorizer is treating the recurrence as a reduction. The initial    │
│ value `<i8 1, i8 0>` is constructed from the reduction's start value (`1`) and the         │
│ identity element for addition (`0`). The reduction is then performed on `splat(i8 1)`,     │
│ which is incorrect.\n\n### Root Cause Analysis ###\n\nThe root cause lies in               │
│ `LoopVectorize.cpp` within the `LoopVectorizePass`. The logic for identifying reduction    │
│ variables is too broad. Specifically, the code checks if a PHI node's value is used in a   │
│ binary operation that feeds back into the PHI. In this case, `add i8 0, %conv678.i.i` is   │
│ treated as a reduction because it's an `add` instruction.\n\nThe fix is to add a check to  │
│ ensure that for a binary operation to be considered part of a reduction, both of its       │
│ operands cannot be loop-invariant. If one operand is the PHI node and the other is a       │
│ loop-invariant constant (like `0` in an `add`), it's not a true reduction if the constant  │
│ is the identity element.\n\nThe proposed change adds a condition to `isReductionPHI` to    │
│ check for this scenario. If the binary operator has an operand that is loop-invariant, it  │
│ will not be considered a reduction, preventing the miscompilation.\n\n### Proposed Edit    │
│ Point(s) ###\n\nI will add a check in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp` to │
│ prevent the misidentification of the recurrence.\n\n```cpp\n// Edit 1:                     │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp:10820\n// Add a check to ensure that not   │
│ all other operands of the reduction operation\n// are loop-invariant.\nif                  │
│ (isa<Constant>(BinOp->getOperand(1 - OpIdx)))\n  continue;\n```\n\nThis change will be     │
│ inserted at line 10820 in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`.\n\n###        │
│ Conclusion ###\n\nBy refining the reduction recognition logic to exclude cases where a     │
│ binary operation involves the reduction PHI and a loop-invariant identity constant, we can │
│ prevent the Loop Vectorizer from incorrectly transforming such recurrences. This fix       │
│ ensures that the vectorizer generates correct code for this and similar cases, resolving   │
│ the miscompilation."})                                                                     │
