│ An incorrect transformation in the Loop Vectorizer is causing a miscompilation. The        │
│ vectorizer is incorrectly identifying a recurrence as a reduction, leading to wrong code   │
│ generation.                                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### Understanding the Issue                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ The provided LLVM IR contains a loop with a recurrence relation defined by a PHI node and  │
│ an `add` instruction:                                                                      │
│ ```llvm                                                                                    │
│ %conv678.i.i = phi i8 [ 1, %entry ], [ %add.i.i.i, %for.body.i.i ]                         │
│ %add.i.i.i = add i8 0, %conv678.i.i                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│ This recurrence is equivalent to `%conv678.i.i_next = %conv678.i.i`, which simply          │
│ propagates the value of `%conv678.i.i` across loop iterations. The initial value is `1`,   │
│ so `%conv678.i.i` remains `1` throughout the loop's execution. The function should return  │
│ `1`.                                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ However, the Loop Vectorizer misidentifies this pattern as an addition reduction. This is  │
│ because it sees a PHI node (`%conv678.i.i`) used in an `add` instruction, with the result  │
│ feeding back into the PHI. Consequently, it generates incorrect vectorized code that       │
│ performs a vector reduction, leading to an incorrect result of `2`, as confirmed by the    │
│ Alive2 verification failure.                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause lies in `RecurrenceDescriptor::isRecurrencePHI` in                          │
│ `LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp`. This function is responsible for identifying recurrence   │
│ variables, including reductions. Its logic is too permissive and incorrectly flags the     │
│ `add i8 0, ...` pattern as a reduction. An `add` or `sub` with a loop-invariant zero is    │
│ not a reduction; it's a simple value propagation.                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to enhance `RecurrenceDescriptor::isRecurrencePHI` to check for this specific   │
│ case. If the instruction is an `add` or `sub`, and one of its operands is a loop-invariant │
│ constant zero, it should not be treated as a reduction.                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### The Fix                                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will add a check at the beginning of `RecurrenceDescriptor::isRecurrencePHI` to handle   │
│ this case.                                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ <tool_call>                                                                                │
│ {                                                                                          │
│   "name": "edit",                                                                          │
│   "args": {                                                                                │
│     "file": "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorizationLegality.cpp",                 │
│     "old": "  // We can only vectorize single-use recurrences.\n  if (!Phi->hasOneUse())\n │
│ return None;",                                                                             │
│     "new": "  // We can only vectorize single-use recurrences.\n  if (!Phi->hasOneUse())\n │
│ return None;\n\n  auto *I = cast<Instruction>(Phi->user_back());\n  unsigned OpIdx =       │
│ (I->getOperand(0) == Phi) ? 0 : 1;\n\n  // If the recurrence is an integer add/sub of a    │
│ loop-invariant zero, it's not a\n  // reduction.\n  if (I->getOpcode() == Instruction::Add │
│ || I->getOpcode() == Instruction::Sub) {\n    if (auto *C =                                │
│ dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1 - OpIdx))) {\n      if (C->isZero())\n        return │
│ None;\n    }\n  }"                                                                         │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ }                                                                                          │
